		<outline title="<![CDATA[Icebox Radio Theater]]>" xmlUrl="http://iceboxradio.libsyn.com/rss" type="rss" text="<![CDATA[Icebox Radio Theater]]>" htmlUrl="http://iceboxradio.libsyn.com/" description="<![CDATA[]The latest from the Icebox Radio Theater - Original audio from the Top of the Nation.  Featuring the best live and studio productions of the Icebox Radio Theater from Int&apos;l Falls, Minnesota.  Bringing the Northland&apos;s Stories to the World.]>"/>
		<outline title="<![CDATA[Prometheus Radio Theatre]]>" xmlUrl="http://prometheus.libsyn.com/rss" type="rss" text="<![CDATA[Prometheus Radio Theatre]]>" htmlUrl="http://www.prometheusradiotheatre.com/" description="<![CDATA[Prometheus Radio Theatre features all-original Science Fiction and Horror audio theatre content.  Prometheus Radio Theatre, a group of experienced Baltimore-area Fan actors, writers and directors, is embarking on what we like to think is a bold, new path (then again, maybe we&apos;re just deranged!)  We&apos;re bringing original, SF radio dramas to Fan audiences at area conventions, and we plan to offer said dramas via CD and streaming audio in the near future.  Our current project is an episodic series, The Arbiter Chronicles, which author Steve Wilson describes as &quot;a sort of Hornblower the Vampire Slayer in Space.&quot;  &quot;Arbiters&quot; tells the tale of young midshipmen (and women) in a future Navy, when the human race has expanded off earth, and things ain&apos;t as bright and cheerful as some might expect.]]>"/>
		<outline title="<![CDATA[ARTC's Podcast]]>" xmlUrl="http://artcpodcast.org/rss" type="rss" text="<![CDATA[ARTC's Podcast]]>" htmlUrl="http://artcpodcast.org/" description="<![CDATA[<h1>ARTC's Podcast</h1><p>A Free Podcast of New Old-Time Radio: Original Radio Plays and adaptations from the Atlanta Radio Theatre Company.&nbsp; <p>Since 1984, the Atlanta Radio Theatre Company has been performing, recording, and broadcasting dramatic audio -- fully dramatized, fully sound-scaped audio drama. We like to think that what we do is classic &#34;old-time radio&#34;, as it would sound with today&apos;s technology and dramatic techniques. From our archives, we proudly present the recordings of our live performances.</p><p>Also visit us at <a href='http://artc.org/'>artc.org</a>.</p>]]>" />
		<outline title="<![CDATA[Texas Radio Theatre Company]]>" xmlUrl="http://texasradio.libsyn.com/rss" type="rss" text="<![CDATA[Texas Radio Theatre Company]]>" htmlUrl="http://texasradio.libsyn.com/" description="<![CDATA[Modern audio drama presented by an award winning group from the Dallas / Fort Worth area.  Most productions have been recorded in front of a studio audience.  The Texas Radio Theatre Company has been recording since 2001.]]>" />
		<outline title="<![CDATA[Tales of the Extraordinary]]>" xmlUrl="http://emptysea.net/tote/podcast1.xml" type="rss" text="<![CDATA[Tales of the Extraordinary]]>" htmlUrl="http://emptysea.net/tote/" description="<![CDATA[A 1920&apos;s Pulp Adventure Serial: The year is 1926...and the Roaring Twenties are in full swing, filled with excess and adventure.  Wondrous new discoveries take place on a daily basis, be they of lost civilizations or miraculous super-science.  Anything seems possible.  In Tales of the Extraordinary, anything is possible.  Ancient mysticism, robotic automatons, masked vigilantes, and monkey-fighting sodomites.  Tales isn&apos;t the way things were.  It&apos;s the way they should&apos;ve been.]]>"/>
